Across our documentation, there isn't a clear enough distinction between {{option}} and {{option2}} in the API. For that matter, there it is rather confusing that each works differently in the REST API.

The [admin docs|https://support.atlassian.com/jira-cloud-administration/docs/custom-fields-types-in-company-managed-projects/] just explain "Select list (single choice)". This leads to confusion when developers are trying to understand [how to create JSON for a custom field|https://support.atlassian.com/jira-software-cloud/docs/advanced-field-editing-json/], where the docs use the term "Single-select custom field". Developers have no way of knowing that is different from the kind of "Single-select custom field" [that can be created via Atlassian Connect|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/jira/platform/using-the-issue-field-module/]. I was unable to find any documentation on how to properly set the {{option2}} custom field.

Although the doc gap might be considered a "bug", what I would really want is not to need more docs. It would be better if the option fields worked the same.

{{option}} works like this:
{code:json}
"customfield_11449" : { "value": "option3" }
{code}
or
{code:json}
"customfield_11449" : { "id": 10112 }
{code}

{{option2}} works like this:
{code:json}
"customfield_11449" : 1
{code}

h3. Issue Summary

When making a REST API request to [get notification schemes|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/jira/platform/rest/v3/api-group-issue-notification-schemes/#api-rest-api-3-notificationscheme-id-get], and the target notification scheme includes UserCustomField or GroupCustomField notifications, then the responsedoes not include an identity.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a notification scheme
 # Add notification of type "User Custom Field Value" and point to an appropriate field
 # Add notification of type "Group Custom Field Value" and point to an appropriate field
 # Invoke the REST API for GET /rest/api/3/notificationscheme/\{id}(where id references the new scheme). Make sure to use {{expand=all}}.

h3. Expected Results

According to the documentation, the response should resemble the following for both UserCustomField and GroupCustomField:
{code:json}
{
...
  "notificationSchemeEvents": [
    "notifications": [
      {
          "id": 6,
          "notificationType": "GroupCustomField",
          "parameter": "customfield_10101",
          "field": {
            "id": "customfield_10101",
            "key": "customfield_10101",
            "name": "New custom field",
            "untranslatedName": "New custom field",
            "custom": true,
            "orderable": true,
            "navigable": true,
            "searchable": true,
            "clauseNames": [
              "cf[10101]",
              "New custom field"
            ],
            "schema": {
              "type": "project",
              "custom": "com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.customfieldtypes:project",
              "customId": 10101
            }
          },
          "expand": "field"
        },
      ...
    ]
  ]
}
{code}

h3. Actual Results

The actual result is missing the field details, even though field is in the expand attribute:
{code:json}
{
...
  "notificationSchemeEvents": [
    "notifications": [
      {
        "id": 10256,
        "notificationType": "GroupCustomField",
        "parameter": "customfield_10132",
        "expand": "field"
      },
      ...
    ]
  ]
}
{code}
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

When making a REST API request to [get notification schemes|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/jira/platform/rest/v3/api-group-issue-notification-schemes/#api-rest-api-3-notificationscheme-id-get], and the target notification scheme includes user notifications, then the response includes an "unknown" user.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a notification scheme
 # Add notification of type "Single User" and point to any user
 # Invoke the REST API for GET /rest/api/3/notificationscheme/\{id}(where id references the new scheme). Make sure to use {{expand=all}}.

h3. Expected Results

According to the documentation, the response should resemble:
{code:json}
{
...
  "notificationSchemeEvents": [
    "notifications": [
      {
        "id": 5,
        "notificationType": "User",
        "parameter": "5b10a2844c20165700ede21g",
        "user": {
          "self": "https://your-domain.atlassian.net/rest/api/3/user?accountId=5b10a2844c20165700ede21g",
          "accountId": "5b10a2844c20165700ede21g",
          "displayName": "Mia Krystof",
          "active": false
        },
        "expand": "user"
      },
      ...
    ]
  ]
}
{code}
h3. Actual Results

The actual result is missing the user id as parameter, and the contained user object:
{code:json}
{
...
  "notificationSchemeEvents": [
    "notifications": [
      {
        "id": 10260,
        "notificationType": "User",
        "parameter": "unknown",
        "expand": "user"
      },
      ...
    ]
  ]
}
{code}
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

We use the Jira REST API to create issues from our running application. On the whole we have found the API to be brittle and awkward to use (eg https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-76190), which means that we often encounter 4XX errors of one sort or another because we have sent somehow invalid input (eg, invalid ADF structure).

In the overwhelming majority of such cases, the response is an HTTP 400 with the body:

{{{}}
{{   "errorMessages": [}}
{{  "We can't create this issue for you right now, it could be due to unsupported content you've entered into one or more of the issue fields. If this situation persists, contact your administrator as they'll be able to access more specific information in the log file."}}
{{   ],}}
{{   "errors": {}}}
{{}}}

There are multiple problems with this:
 # This response is generated when input is well formed, ie, valid JSON, but does not conform to schema. That means that HTTP 400 is the wrong choice semantically - it should be a 422.
 # The message is uninformative. It may be the case that our IT team have access to this log file, but it is no use to them - _we_ need the error in the response because we, as developers, are the ones empowered to fix this. If you can write a meaningful error message to a file, then you can write it to a response stream.
 # If you _can't_ write it to a file and/or stream, then IMO that should be a 500 - the error is not being handled. And it should therefore be treated as a bug rather than 'normal' operation.

h3. Issue Summary
Setting a single select field to "none" for a dynamic field in a Connect App does not change the data.
 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create custom issue field using dynamic module rest api. Using {{POST}} method to {{{/rest/atlassian-connect/1/app/module/dynamic}}, send: {code:json}
"jiraIssueFields":[
  {
    "key":"team-issue-field",
    "name":{
      "value":"Team"
    },
    "description":{
      "value":"Team tied to issue"
    },
    "type":"single_select",
    "extractions":[
      {
        "path":"category",
        "type":"string",
        "name":"category"
      }
    ]
  }
]
{code}
 # Add option to newly created custom issue field. Using create api for connect app following this rest api: https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/jira/platform/rest/v3/api-group-issue-custom-field-options--apps-/#api-rest-api-3-field-fieldkey-option-post
 # Select one option in the newly created custom issue field in jira project issue:
 # Try to deselect option, set to none - it will work visually
 # Refresh the page, to check if the field value has been saved.

h3. Expected Results
The option has been set to none, as was shown in the UI.

h3. Actual Results
The option has returned to the set value, in disagreement with the UI.

h3. Workaround
 Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available.

h3. Issue Summary

Non-batched Notifications bypass Personal Settings notification options. This means that even if we disable the *Email notifications for issue activity* to block notifications, the e-mails will still be delivered.

h3. Steps to Reproduce

There are 2 scenarios where Jira won't use the Batched Notifications, being them:


{panel}
* When using "custom from domains" (e.g. they use jira@mydomain.com) configured on their instance.
* When customizing the "from name" of emails from their instance (away from the default of "${fullname} (Jira)").
{panel}


# Access *System* > *General Settings* > *Edit Settings*;
# Update the *Email from* to something different then the default, e.g. Custom Email From;
# Click on your *Profile Picture* > *Personal Settings*;
# Change the *Email notifications for issue activity* to *Don't send me e-mail notifications*;
# With a different account, perform an action on a ticket. e.g. Comment on the ticket;

_Obs: Keep in mind that you must also consider the Notification Scheme and ensure that the action (issue updated, issue commented, etc) will trigger a notification._

h3. Expected Results

No notification will be sent to the user.

h3. Actual Results

The message is delivered.

h3. Workaround

Use the default value *${fullname} (Jira)* on the Email From setting.

h3. Issue Summary

Upon completion of a request that changed the field permission on the `duedate` field, which is one of several fields that our Jira add-on app will sometimes update, all PUT payloads to Jira API `/rest/api/3/issue/\{issue-key}` that included `duedate` in the payload failed with Jira responding with 400.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Restrict the permissions of an issue field, in this case `duedate`, so that it does not appear on the edit screen of an issue
 # Attempt to perform a PUT update on that field using the Jira API from you Jira add-on app
 # Receive the following error:

PUT [https://asecurityteam.atlassian.net/rest/api/3/issue/VULN-283408]
Payload:
```
{
    "fields": {
        "customfield_10607": [{
            "accountId": "5ea93d41c112750bab4d34ae"
        }, {
            "accountId": "557057:51b1c618-8a53-4fb5-83d1-c5de6f231e5a"
        }],
        "customfield_10273": {
            "value": "Confluence Server",
            "child": {
                "value": "Little Big Platform"
            }
        },
        "customfield_10599": {
            "value": "Within SLO"
        },
        "customfield_10609": "2021-02-23",
        "duedate": "2021-05-24"
    }
}
```
Response was 400 with:
```
{
    "errorMessages": [],
    "errors": {
        "duedate": "Field 'duedate' cannot be set. It is not on the appropriate screen, or unknown."
    }
}
```

h3. Expected Results

The permissions of the edit screen of an issue should not affect the permissions of the Jira API.
h3. Actual Results

The below exception is thrown in the xxxxxxx.log file:
{noformat}
{
    "errorMessages": [],
    "errors": {
        "duedate": "Field 'duedate' cannot be set. It is not on the appropriate screen, or unknown."
    }
}
{noformat}
h3. Workaround


Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available
